    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-11T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-11T09:00:00-05:00" n="299"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d299">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/337</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-11T14:00:00+00:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">August 11, 1914, 2 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11:15 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> informs me that Japan
                    finds herself unable to refrain from war with Germany, The German Ambassador at
                        <pb facs="0482" n="168" xml:id="pg_168"/> Tokyo has made further refraining
                    impossible. Japan assures Britain that she is anxious to respect both the
                    neutrality and the integrity of China. The Anglo-Japanese treaty binds both
                    parties to it to respect her integrity.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
